Here's a clean implementation using the MVVM Community Toolkit, which eliminates boilerplate:

```csharp
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.ComponentModel;
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.Input;

namespace YourApp.ViewModels;

public partial class ProductDetailViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _name = string.Empty;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private decimal _price;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _isAvailable;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _isLoading;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task LoadAsync()
    {
        IsLoading = true;
        try
        {
            // Replace with your actual data service call
            await Task.Delay(500);
            Name = "Widget Pro";
            Price = 29.99m;
            IsAvailable = true;
        }
        finally
        {
            IsLoading = false;
        }
    }
}
```

**How it works:**

- `[ObservableProperty]` source-generates public properties (`Name`, `Price`, etc.) with `INotifyPropertyChanged` calls — write the backing field, get the property for free.
- `[RelayCommand]` generates a public `LoadCommand` (IAsyncRelayCommand) from `LoadAsync`, which also gives you automatic `CanExecute` management during execution.
- The class must be `partial` so the source generator can emit the other half.

**NuGet package needed:**
```
dotnet add package CommunityToolkit.Mvvm
```

**Binding in XAML:**
```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels">
    <ContentPage.BindingContext>
        <vm:ProductDetailViewModel />
    </ContentPage.BindingContext>

    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="16">
        <Label Text="{Binding Name}" FontSize="24" />
        <Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='${0:F2}'}" />
        <Label Text="{Binding IsAvailable, StringFormat='In Stock: {0}'}" />
        <ActivityIndicator IsRunning="{Binding IsLoading}" />
        <Button Text="Load Product" Command="{Binding LoadCommand}" />
    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```
